Claims CLAIMS WHAT IS CLAIMED IS: 1. A method for assessing a mental state of a subject in a single session or over multiple different sessions, said method comprising: using an automated module to present and/or formulate at least one query based in part on one or more target mental states to be assessed, wherein said at least one query is configured to elicit at least one response from said subject; transmitting said at least one query in an audio, visual, and/or textual format to said subject to elicit said at least one response; receiving data comprising said at least one response from said subject in response to transmitting said at least one query, wherein said data comprises speech data; processing said data using one or more individual, joint, or fused models comprising a natural language processing (NLP) model, an acoustic model, and/or a visual model; and generating, for said single session, for each of said multiple different sessions, or upon completion of one or more sessions of said multiple different sessions, one or more assessments of said mental state associated with said subject. 2. The method of claim 1 , wherein said at least one query comprises a plurality of queries and said at least one response comprises a plurality of responses, wherein said plurality of queries is transmitted in a sequential manner to said subject and configured to systematically elicit said plurality of responses from said subject. 3. The method of claim 2, wherein said plurality of queries is structured in a hierarchical manner such that each subsequent query of said plurality of queries is structured as a logical follow on to said subjectâs response to a preceding query, and is designed to assess or draw inferences on a plurality of aspects of said mental state of said subject. 4. The method of claim 1 , wherein said automated module is further configured to present and/or formulate said at least one query based in part on a profile of said subject. 5. The method of claim 1 , wherein said one or more target mental states is selected from the group consisting of depression, anxiety, post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), schizophrenia, suicidality, and bipolar disorder. 6. The method of claim 1 , wherein said one or more target mental states comprise one or more conditions or disorders associated or comorbid with a list of predefined mental disorders. 7. The method of claim 6, wherein said one or more conditions or disorders comprise fatigue, loneliness, low motivation, or stress. 8. The method of claim 1 , wherein said assessment comprises a score that indicates whether said subject is (i) more likely than others to experience at least one of said target mental states or (ii) more likely than others to experience at least one of said target mental states at a future point in time. 9. The method of claim 8, wherein said future point in time is within a clinically actionable future. 10. The method of claim 1 , further comprising: transmitting said assessment to a healthcare provider to be used in evaluating said mental state of said subject, wherein said transmitting is performed in real-time during said assessment, just-in-time, or after said assessment is completed. 11. The method of claim 3 , wherein said plurality of queries is designed to test for or detect said plurality of aspects of said mental state of said subject. 12. The method of claim 2, wherein said assessment comprises a score that indicates whether said subject is (i) more likely than others to experience at least one of said target mental states or (ii) more likely than others to experience at least one of said target mental states at a future point in time, wherein said score is calculated based on processed data obtained from said subjectâs plurality of responses to said plurality of queries. 13. The method of claim 12, wherein said score is continuously updated with processed data obtained from each of said subjectâs follow-on response to a preceding query. 14. The method of claim 1 , further comprising: based on said at least one response, identifying additional information to be elicited from said subject; transmitting a subsequent query to said subject, wherein said subsequent query relates to said additional information and is configured to elicit a subsequent response from said subject; receiving data comprising said subsequent response from said subject in response to transmitting said subsequent query, and processing said subsequent response to update said assessment of said mental state of said subject. 15. The method of claim 14, wherein identifying additional information to be elicited from said subject comprises: identifying (i) one or more elements of substantive content or (ii) one or more patterns in said data that are material to said mental state of said subject; and for each of said one or more elements of substantive content or said one or more patterns: identifying one or more items of follow-up information that are related to said one or more elements or said one or more patterns to be asked of said subject, and generating a subsequent query, wherein said subsequent query relates to said one or more items of follow-up information. 16. The method of claim 1 , wherein said NLP model is selected from the group consisting of a sentiment model, a statistical language model, a topic model, a syntactic model, an embedding model, a dialog or discourse model, an emotion or affect model, and a speaker personality model. 17. The method of claim 1 , wherein said data further comprises images or video of said subject, and wherein said data is further processed using said visual model to generate said assessment of said mental state of said subject. 18. The method of claim 17, wherein said visual model is selected from the group consisting of a facial cue model, a body movement/motion model, and an eye activity model. 19. The method of claim 1 , wherein said at least one query is transmitted in a conversational context in a form of a question, statement, or comment that is configured to elicit said at least one response from said subject. 20. The method of claim 19, wherein said conversational context is designed to promote elicitation of truthful, reflective, thoughtful, or candid responses from said subject. 21. The method of claim 20, wherein said conversational context is designed to affect an amount of time that said subject takes to compose said at least one response. 22. The method of claim 21 , further comprising: transmitting one or more prompts in said audio and/or visual format to said subject when a time latency threshold is exceeded. 23. The method of claim 19, wherein said conversational context is designed to enhance one or more performance metrics of said assessment of said mental state of said subject. 24. The method of claim 23, wherein said one or more performance metrics is selected from the group consisting of an Fl score, an area under the curve (AUC), a sensitivity, a specificity, a positive predictive value (PPV), and an equal error rate. 25. The method of claim 1 , wherein said at least one query is not transmitted or provided in a format of a standardized test or questionnaire. 26. The method of claim 1 , wherein said at least one query comprises subject matter that has been adapted or modified from a standardized test or questionnaire. 27. The method of claims 25 or 26, wherein said standardized test or questionnaire is selected from the group consisting of PHQ-9, GAD-7, HAM-D, and BDI. 28. The method of claim 1 , wherein said one or more individual, joint, or fused models comprise a regression model. 29. The method of claim 1 , wherein said at least one query is designed to be open- ended without limiting said at least one response from said subject to be a binary yes-or-no response. 30. The method of claim 8, wherein said score is used to calculate one or more scores with a clinical value. 31. The method of claim 1 , wherein said assessment comprises a quantized score estimate of said mental state of said subject. 32. The method of claim 31 , wherein said quantized score estimate comprises a calibrated score estimate. 33. The method of claim 31 , wherein said quantized score estimate comprise a binary score estimate. 34. The method of claim 2, wherein said plurality of queries is represented as a series of edges and said plurality of responses is represented as a series of nodes in a nodal network. 35. The method of claim 1 , wherein said mental state comprises one or more medical, psychological, or psychiatric conditions or symptoms. 36. The method of claim 1 , wherein said method is capable of further assessing a physical state of said subject as manifested based on said speech data of said subject, said method further comprising: processing said data using said one or more individual, joint, or fused models to generate an assessment of said physical state of said subject, wherein said assessment of said physical state comprises a score that indicates whether said subject is (i) more likely than others to experience at least one of a plurality of physiological conditions or (ii) more likely 

 than others to experience at least one of said physiological conditions at a future point in time. 37. The method of claim 36, wherein said physical state of said subject is manifested due to one or more physical conditions that affect a characteristic or a quality of voice of said subject. 38. A non-transitory computer readable-medium comprising machine-executable instructions that, upon execution by one or more computer processors, implements a method for assessing a mental state of a subject in a single session or over multiple different sessions, said method comprising: presenting and/or formulating at least one query based in part on one or more target mental states to be assessed, wherein said at least one query is configured to elicit at least one response from said subject; transmitting said at least one query in an audio, visual, or textual format to said subject to elicit said at least one response; receiving data comprising said at least one response from said subject in response to transmitting said at least one query, wherein said data comprises speech data; and processing said data using one or more individual, joint, or fused models comprising a natural language processing (NLP) model, an acoustic model, and/or a visual model; and generating, for said single session, for each of said multiple different sessions, or upon completion of one or more sessions of said multiple different sessions, one or more assessments of said mental state associated with said subject. 39. A system comprising: one or more computer processors; and memory comprising machine-executable instructions that, upon execution by said one or more computer processors, implements a method for assessing a mental state of a subject in a single session or over multiple different sessions, said method comprising: presenting and/or formulating at least one query based in part on one or more target mental states to be assessed, wherein said at least one query is configured to elicit at least one response from said subject; transmitting said at least one query in an audio, visual, and/or textual format to said subject to elicit said at least one response; 

 receiving data comprising said at least one response from said subject in response to transmitting said at least one query, wherein said data comprises speech data; and processing said data using one or more individual, joint, or fused models comprising a natural language processing (NLP) model, an acoustic model, and/or a visual model; and generating, for said single session, for each of said multiple different sessions, or upon completion of one or more sessions of said multiple different sessions, one or more assessments of said mental state associated with said subject. 40. The method of claim 1 , wherein said automated module is a mental health screening module that is configured to dynamically formulate said at least one query based in part on said one or more target mental states to be assessed. 41. The method of claim 1 , wherein said one or more individual, joint, or fused models comprises a composite model that is an aggregate of two or more different models. 42. A method for screening or monitoring a subject for or diagnosing said subject with a mental health disorder, comprising: (a) transmitting at least one query to said subject, wherein said at least one query is configured to elicit at least one response from said subject; (b) receiving data comprising said at least one response from said subject in response to transmitting said at least one query, wherein said data comprises speech data; (c) processing said data using one or more individual, joint, or fused models comprising a natural language processing (NLP) model, an acoustic model, and/or a visual model to generate an output; and (d) using at least said output to generate a score and a confidence level of said score, wherein said score comprises an estimate that said subject has said mental health disorder, and wherein said confidence level is based at least in part on a quality of said speech data and represents a degree to which said estimate can be trusted. 43. The method of claim 42, wherein said output comprises an NLP output, an acoustic output, and a visual output. 44. The method of claim 43, wherein said NLP output, said acoustic output, and said visual output each comprise a plurality of outputs corresponding to different time ranges of said data. 45. The method of claim 44, wherein generating said score comprises: (i) segmenting said NLP output, said acoustic output, and said visual output into discrete time segments, (ii) assigning a weight to each discrete time segment, and (iii) computing a weighted average of said NLP output, said acoustic output, and said visual output using said assigned weights. 46. The method of claim 45, wherein said weights are based at least on (i) base weights of said one or more individual, joint, or fused models (ii) a confidence level of each discrete time segment of said NLP output, said acoustic output, and said visual output. 47. The method of claim 43, wherein said one or more individual, joint, or fused models are interdependent such that each of said one or more individual, joint, or fused models are conditioned on an output of at least one other of said one or more individual, joint, or fused models. 48. The method of claim 43, wherein generating said score comprises fusing said NLP output, said acoustic output, and said visual output. 49. The method of claim 48, wherein generating said confidence level of said score comprises fusing (i) a confidence level of said NLP output with (ii) a confidence level of said acoustic output. 50. The method of claim 42, further comprising converting said score into one or more scores with a clinical value. 51. The method of claim 50, further comprising transmitting said one or more scores with a clinical value to said subject and/or a contact for said subject. 52. The method of claim 50, further comprising transmitting said one or more scores with a clinical value to a healthcare provider for use in evaluating and/or providing care for a mental health of said subject. 53. The method claim 52, wherein said transmitting comprises transmitting said one or more scores with a clinical value to said healthcare provider during said screening, monitoring, or diagnosing. 54. The method of claim 52, wherein said transmitting comprises transmitting said one or more scores with a clinical value to said healthcare provider or a payer after said screening, monitoring, or diagnosing is completed. 55. The method of claim 42, wherein said at least one query comprises a plurality of queries, wherein said at least one response comprises a plurality of responses, wherein generating said score comprises updating said score after receiving each of said plurality of responses, and wherein said method further comprises: converting said score to one or more scores with a clinical value after each of said updates; and transmitting said one or more scores with a clinical value to a healthcare provider after said converting. 56. The method of claim 42, further comprising: determining that said confidence level does not satisfy a predetermined criterion; in real time and based at least in part on said at least one response, generating at least one additional query, and using said at least one additional query, repeating steps (a) - (d) until said confidence level satisfies said predetermined criterion. 57. The method of claim 42, wherein said confidence level is based on a length of said at least one response. 58. The method of claim 42, wherein said confidence level is based on an evaluated truthfulness of said one or more responses of said subject. 59. The method of claim 42, wherein said one or more individual, joint, or fused models are trained on speech data from a plurality of test subjects, wherein each of said plurality of test subjects has completed a survey or questionnaire that indicates whether said test subject has said mental health disorder, and wherein said confidence level is based on an evaluated truthfulness of responses in said survey or questionnaire. 60. The method of claim 42, further comprising extracting from said speech data one or more topics of concern of said subject using a topic model. 61. The method of claim 60, further comprising generating a word cloud from said one or more topics of concern, wherein said word cloud reflects changes in said one or more topics of concern of said subject over time. 62. The method of claim 60, further comprising transmitting said one or more topics of concern to a healthcare provider, said subject, or both. 63. The method of claim 43, wherein said video output is assigned a higher weight than said NLP output and said acoustic output in generating said score when said subject is not speaking. 64. The method of claim 43, wherein a weight of said video output in generating said score is increased when said NLP output and said acoustic output indicate that a truthfulness level of said subject is below a threshold. 65. The method of claim 43, wherein said video model comprises one or more of a facial cue model, a body movement/motion model, and a gaze model. 66. The method of claim 42, wherein said at least one query comprises a plurality of queries and said at least one response comprises a plurality of responses, wherein said plurality of queries is configured to sequentially and systematically elicit said plurality of responses from said subject, wherein said plurality of queries is structured in a hierarchical manner such that each subsequent query of said plurality of queries is a logical follow on to said subjectâs response to a preceding query and is designed to assess or draw inferences about different aspects of said mental state of said subject. 67. The method of claim 42, wherein said at least one query includes subject matter that has been adapted or modified from a chnically- validated survey, test or questionnaire. 68. The method of claim 42, wherein said acoustic model comprises one or more of an acoustic embedding model, a spectral-temporal model, a supervector model, an acoustic affect model, a speaker personality model, an intonation model, a speaking rate model, a pronunciation model, a non-verbal model, or a fluency model. 69. The method of claim 42, wherein said NLP model comprises one or more of a sentiment model, a statistical language model, a topic model, a syntactic model, an embedding model, a dialog or discourse model, an emotion or affect model, or a speaker personality model. 70. The method of claim 42, wherein said mental health disorder comprises depression, anxiety, post-traumatic stress disorder, bipolar disorder, suicidality or schizophrenia. 71. The method of claim 42, wherein said mental health disorder comprises one or more medical, psychological, or psychiatric conditions or symptoms. 72. The method of claim 42, wherein said score comprises a score selected from a range, wherein said range is normalized with respect to a general population or to a specific population of interest. 73. The method of claim of 12, wherein said one or more scores with a clinical value comprises one or more descriptors associated with said mental health disorder. 74. The method of claim 42, wherein steps (a) - (d) are repeated at a plurality of different times to generate a plurality of scores, and wherein said method further comprises: transmitting said plurality of scores and confidences to a computing device; and graphically displaying, on said computing device, said plurality of scores and 

