onfigured to store speech data of said subject; and one or more computer processors operatively coupled to said memory, wherein said one or more computer processors are individually or collectively programmed to (i) receive said speech data from said memory and (ii) process said speech data using at least one model to determine that said subject is at risk of having said mental condition, wherein said at least one model is trained on speech data from a plurality of other test subjects who have a clinical determination of said mental condition, and wherein said system is configured to generate said estimate of said mental condition that is better according to one or more performance metrics as compared to a clinically- validated survey, test or questionnaire. 117. The system of claim 116, wherein said system is configured to generate said estimate of said mental condition with a higher specificity compared to said clinically- validated survey, test or questionnaire. 118. The system of claim 116, wherein said system is configured to generate said estimate of said mental condition with a higher sensitivity compared to said clinically- validated survey, test, or questionnaire. 119. The method of claim 81 , wherein said identification is output while said subject is speaking. 120. The method of claim 119, wherein said identification is output via streaming or a periodically updated signal. 121. The method of claim 1 , wherein said one or more individual, joint, or fused models comprise a metadata model, wherein said metadata model is configured to use demographic information and/or a medical history of said subject to generate said one or more assessments of said mental state associated with said subject. 122. A method for assessing a mental state of a subject, comprising: using an automated screening module to dynamically formulate at least one query based in part on one or more target mental states to be assessed, wherein said at least one query is configured to elicit